00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:49.599
This isn't necessarily a question, but I saw a lot of excitement the past two days about Shiny Express.

00:12:50.599 --> 00:12:56.599
And I was just wondering if either of you from the Shiny team could share a little bit about that.

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:01.599
Yeah, I guess I'll keep going.

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:13.599
So Shiny Express is essentially like a new syntax mode for writing Shiny apps in Python.

00:13:15.599 --> 00:13:22.599
So it allows you to essentially intermingle UI and server code.

00:13:23.599 --> 00:13:46.599
So instead of having a separate UI object and a separate server function, you get to essentially mix the two, which allows you to write more succinct Shiny code where you can essentially write a render function directly in a script.

00:13:46.599 --> 00:13:55.599
And then that effectively transforms itself into an output container with a server render function.

00:13:58.599 --> 00:14:09.599
So Shiny Express itself is built on Shiny, what we're calling Shiny core, which is the way that you're used to writing Shiny apps in R essentially.

00:14:11.599 --> 00:14:15.599
And that way of writing Shiny apps is not going anywhere.

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:28.599
We kind of view that as the way that you're going to want to write Shiny apps on a project where you really value long-term maintainability and flexibility.

00:14:29.599 --> 00:14:40.599
Because Express, like it says in the name, does take some shortcuts to make it easier to learn and write Shiny apps, but it's going to be a little bit more restrictive in what you're able to do with it.

00:14:41.599 --> 00:14:46.599
So we're hoping it's going to be a nice on-ramp for people. It's a lot quicker to get started.

00:14:47.599 --> 00:14:53.599
Even development-wise, it's really nice to type less to create an example.

00:14:54.599 --> 00:15:15.599
But again, for more serious projects where you're going to want to put this thing in production and test it and work on a team of people potentially to develop this app and write good modular code, the classic way of writing Shiny apps is still, we think, best in that kind of context.

00:15:17.599 --> 00:15:18.599
Thank you.

00:15:19.599 --> 00:15:22.599
And Shiny Express is solely for Python at the moment, right?

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:24.599
It is solely for Python.

00:15:28.599 --> 00:15:30.599
It's not like we couldn't bring this to R as well.

00:15:31.599 --> 00:15:49.599
But one thing also worth pointing out here about Shiny Express and the possibility of bringing it to R is that we already have something that feels pretty close to Shiny Express with our markdown documents with runtime Shiny mode.

00:15:50.599 --> 00:16:08.599
If you look at Shiny Express apps, they're quite similar to that same style of with your RMD document with runtime Shiny, you can essentially just inline a render plot statement and then it renders a plot there that's fully interactive.

00:16:09.599 --> 00:16:15.599
It's a very similar kind of concept and style for Shiny Express.

00:16:20.599 --> 00:16:21.599
Thank you.

