I'd say that a lot of it is built around looking or trying our best to look good at all different screen sizes.

00:23:31.599 --> 00:23:35.599
One of the things that I noticed in this one was that we were in this app.

00:23:35.599 --> 00:23:40.599
We were zooming in quite a bit to try to make sure that everything was readable for the video.

00:23:40.599 --> 00:23:48.599
And I think the experience if you are developing locally or if you were actually looking at the app on your desktop would be a little bit different.

00:23:49.599 --> 00:23:53.599
We also in the last year introduced an idea of fillability.

00:23:53.599 --> 00:24:03.599
This is a slightly advanced concept, but we have some nice articles on the BS Lib page that can help with that.

00:24:03.599 --> 00:24:09.599
The general idea is that, especially in dashboards, you have these UI components or you have plots

00:24:09.599 --> 00:24:14.599
where they really want to take up the full height and width of the cell that they're in.

00:24:14.599 --> 00:24:21.599
So you kind of want to have a plot that fills up the entire card rather than being just a fixed size.

00:24:21.599 --> 00:24:31.599
And often playing with the settings for whether something is fillable, as in it fills its container.

00:24:31.599 --> 00:24:34.599
You can get to different layouts.

00:24:35.599 --> 00:24:40.599
It depends a lot on the type of thing that you're trying to put into your dashboard.

00:24:41.599 --> 00:24:45.599
Maybe one more just quick question.

00:24:45.599 --> 00:24:49.599
Does thematic work well with Plotly?

00:24:49.599 --> 00:24:55.599
It's funny, we were just talking about this in private before the chat here.

00:24:55.599 --> 00:24:59.599
But partially, yes.

00:25:00.599 --> 00:25:19.599
If you're using ggplotly, then Plotly does a little bit of extra work to make sure that the result that you would get with ggplot2 and thematic is going to be the same as what you'll get with ggplotly in Plotly.

00:25:19.599 --> 00:25:34.599
But if you're using the core Plotly API, if you're not using ggplot2 at all, then the Plotly graph will not respect whatever you're doing with thematic.

00:25:34.599 --> 00:26:03.599
And it would be nice to, I don't know if the answer is for Plotly to respect thematic, but I think Plotly could certainly do a little bit more to be, at least give you an option to say, I want to be informed, like whatever styling is in my container in the Shiny app, this Plotly graph should use, inherit those styles a little bit better.

00:26:05.599 --> 00:26:09.599
So I would like for that to be a feature someday, for sure.

